he initial results are correct, V2 will win again, and you can draw some le=
arnings that you can propagate across the site.</span></p><p><span style=3D=
"font-weight: 400;">You should also consider allocating 100% of the traffic=
 to the winning variation. This means pausing the experiment, duplicating i=
t, and resetting the traffic allocation.</span></p><h3><span style=3D"font-=
weight: 400;">Scenario 2: Multiple Winning Variations:</span></h3><p><b>Wha=
t it means:</b><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"> Sometimes, depending on h=
ow reasonable your </span><a href=3D"https://www.invespcro.com/blog/expert-=
advice-on-developing-a-hypothesis-for-marketing-experimentation/"><span sty=
le=3D"font-weight: 400;">developed hypothesis</span></a><span style=3D"font=
-weight: 400;"> was, more than one variation can outperform the control, bu=
t it needs to be clarified which one is the absolute best.</span></p><p><sp=
an style=3D"font-weight: 400;">As good as it might sound, it can be confusi=
